and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Dalton was born in 1380, in Bispham, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir John Dalton jr, was 46 and his mother, Isabel de Pilkington, was 14. He had at least 5 sons with Margaret Holker. He died in 1444, in Bispham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1380–1444":"1380–1444","1384–Female":"1384–Surnud","1390–1442":"1390–1442","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1441–Male":"1441–Surnud","1443–Male":"1443–Surnud","1445–1500":"1445–1500","1447–1517":"1447–1517","1447–Male":"1447–Surnud","1334–1389":"1334–1389","1367–1406":"1367–1406","about 1380":"umbes 1380"